I have a neutral opinion on books. I loved plenty of popular kids’ books during my childhood, like Geronimo Stilton (the one you mentioned) and everyone’s favorite, Captain Underpants. (I always thought way too hard about the time travel stuff.)

And then high school was like “Hey kid... wanna read some classic literature?” And I didn’t really take much interest. I found a few of these books a little bit interesting, but these are books I NEVER would’ve picked up on my own accord.

Though I read a LOT less now, I’ve recently picked up a book called Creativity, Inc. by Ed Catmull, one of the guys who helped found Pixar. I’m hoping it can shed a little bit of light about how they do the things they do.

(Also, was that an Ace Attorney reference at 5:10? I’ve been playing that game nonstop until Animal Crossing.)

snippet.textDisplay:
I hate that the academic system forces people to read specific books and says "these books are good!"
Whether they're masterpieces or not, reading is something one absolutely should enjoy, because it's one of few foolproof ways to detach yourself from stress and get completely immersed in a (non)fictional world in a healthy manner.
I loved that aspect, and my mom gladly encouraged my love of reading kids books, to eventually easy chapter books, to the point that even when I was forced to read something for school, I took it objectively, and found that I could enjoy a lot more than just fantasy novels. I even enjoyed books like The Scarlet Letter, Voltaire's Candide, Canterbury Tales, and Dante's Inferno, simply because I found my enjoyment and appreciation of a book can go much deeper when I begin to analyze the metaphors, symbols, and character motivations. And.. Well, doing that is the only way one can really analyze those ancient things. (Now I nerd out over any sort of narrative, written or film, that has underlying symbolism)


Reading is a love that has to be carefully crafted when a child is young, and then encouraged and nurtured. Reading should not and cannot be forced, and I get really sad whenever I hear from somebody that they hate reading.


For anybody willing to read through my tiny essay, I wanna start a thread! Give me your favorite book, a book you're currently reading, and a book you plan on reading. For me, it's...


Favorite Book: The Book Thief (Fitting, right?)
Currently reading: Miss Peregrine's Peculiar Children- A Map of Days (on hiatus rn because college)
Gonna Read Next: The Silmarillion (my roommate gushes about it, so I thought why not?)
